</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Ireland headed for early general elections when the Labor Party broke off 
talks on rebuilding a coalition with Fianna Fail in a fresh dispute over a 
child-abuse case that toppled their government. Labor leader Dick Spring told 
Parliament that his party is ready to fight in elections if attempts to form an 
alternative coalition fail. Spring, who holds the balance of power in the 
165-seat lower house, said he was pulling out because Fianna Fail misled him 
about the bungled government handling of extradition warrants for a pedophile 
priest. 
