<HEADLINE>
<P>
BOARD OKS FUNDS TO CONTINUE COSTLY HOSPITAL BILLING SYSTEM; FINANCES: THE 
COUNTY IS SETTING ASIDE $6.8 MILLION TO HANDLE COSTS FOR 18 MONTHS. IBAX HAD 
BEEN LAUDED AS STATE OF THE ART, BUT HAS PROVED AN EMBARRASSMENT. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By TIMOTHY WILLIAMS, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Los Angeles County supervisors Tuesday approved spending $6.8 million to 
continue operating a hospital computer system that was designed to make patient 
bill collecting more efficient but has cost more than $10 million to fix. 
</P>
<P>
 Although estimates vary, county officials say the IBAX computer system has 
lost between $2 million and $17 million in hospital billings that might not be 
retrievable. The county canceled the IBAX contract in June after an 
investigation of the system's shortcomings. 
</P>
<P>
 The $6.8 million approved Tuesday came out of the Health Services Department 
budget for non-patient service, an amount that had been set aside in case an 
alternative billing system was needed, according to Kathryn Barger, a health 
deputy for Supervisor Mike Antonovich. Instead, supervisors decided to spend 
the money in an attempt to improve the system. 
</P>
<P>
 The funds will cover costs for the next 18 months, including a computer 
consultant and two computer firms helping to develop a new billing system. 
</P>
<P>
 "What we are trying to do is integrate the new system with IBAX so we don't 
risk losing any more billings," Barger said. 
</P>
<P>
 In the meantime, county officials are searching for a replacement system to 
handle Medi-Cal and other billing at two county hospitals. 
</P>
<P>
 IBAX, which cost $65 million, has been both a frustration and an embarrassment 
to the cash-strapped county. 
</P>
<P>
 Supervisor Gloria Molina has taken the lead in pursuing alternatives. "This 
IBAX monster failed us miserably," Molina said during Tuesday's meeting. "We 
need to get this behind us as quickly as we can." 
</P>
<P>
 The board's decision came a week after the county reached a settlement with 
IBAX in which the firm paid $3 million in cash and $5.5 million in credits to 
purchase medical supplies and computer-related equipment. Neither side admitted 
wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
 When the Board of Supervisors awarded IBAX the hospital billing contract in 
late 1990, the system was billed as state of the art, capable of replacing 
myriad contractors and in-house methods that were failing to promptly bill 
patients, insurance companies and other providers for hospital health care 
costs. 
</P>
<P>
 The system was installed first at High Desert Hospital in Lancaster and Rancho 
Los Amigos Medical Center in Downey and was planned to be used in four other 
county hospitals. It was projected to save more than $10 million by the time 
its contract expired in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
