<HEADLINE>
<P>
KNOTT'S PLANS NEW ROLLER COASTER; ENTERTAINMENT: THE JAGUAR IS SCHEDULED TO 
DEBUT MEMORIAL DAY. A PARK SPOKESMAN SAYS THE RIDE WILL COMPLEMENT DISNEYLAND'S 
NEW INDIANA JONES ATTRACTION AND BOOST O.C. TOURISM. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHRIS WOODYARD, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Hoping to lift its summer attendance to new heights, Knott's Berry Farm 
unveiled plans Tuesday for a new thrill ride. 
</P>
<P>
 Called Jaguar, the new steel roller coaster will give passengers a four-minute 
ride -- about a minute more than most similar roller coasters, Knott's 
officials said. The coaster will cost more than $10 million to build and is 
projected to open by Memorial Day, the unofficial start of the summer tourism 
season. 
</P>
<P>
 The ride will open shortly after nearby Disneyland unveils its splashiest ride 
in years: an adventure ride based on the Indiana Jones film trilogy. 
</P>
<P>
 Knott's said the parks will complement -- not compete against -- each other 
next summer. 
</P>
<P>
 "With both Orange County parks unveiling new attractions, it could be the year 
that tourists return to Southern California," said Bob Ochsner, a Knott's 
spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
 The ride will become the centerpiece of the Fiesta Village section of the 
theme park. At 2,600 feet, it will be long enough to travel over a sixth of the 
park's area. It will zoom over a lake, thread through a 45-foot loop and then 
climb to the top of a tower. 
</P>
<P>
 Roller coasters are the most popular of theme park attractions, said Paul 
Ruben, Northern American editor of Park World, a theme park industry weekly 
based in England. Because they are such a draw, he said, they generally pay for 
themselves within two years of operation through increased attendance. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's the No. 1 reason people visit theme parks," Ruben said. 
</P>
<P>
 The Jaguar will be the second major new attraction at Knott's within a year. 
Mystery Lodge opened this year as a theater in which Native Americans tell 
stories while images appear in simulated campfire smoke. 
</P>
<P>
 Ochsner said the new roller coaster has been planned for five years. Park 
President Terry E. Van Gorder said in interviews earlier this year that he had 
been hesitant to launch new rides earlier because California was deeply 
entrenched in recession. 
</P>
<P>
 (BEGIN TEXT OF INFOBOX / INFOGRAPHIC) The Jaguar 
</P>
<P>
 Knott's Berry Farm plans to have a new roller coaster completed in time for 
the park's 75th anniversary celebration next summer. Facts about the ride: 
</P>
<P>
 * Name: Jaguar 
</P>
<P>
 * Opening date: May 30 (Memorial Day) 
</P>
<P>
 * Length: 2,700 feet 
</P>
<P>
 * Height: 60 feet 
</P>
<P>
 * Capacity: 24-passenger trains able to carry 1,500 guests an hour 
</P>
<P>
 * Location: Fiesta Village 
</P>
<P>
 * Cost: More than $10 million 
</P>
<P>
 * Builder: Zierer GmbH, Offenberg, Germany 
</P>
<P>
 Source: Knott's Berry Farm; Researched by CHRIS WOODYARD / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</TEXT>
